<P>General Amher&s;t, who was the fir&s;t Briti&s;h general in command in America, conducted the &s;econd exp<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">|dition. His orders were, to reduce all Canada, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> join the army under general Wolfe on the banks of the river St. Lawrence. He was &s;o well provided <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> every thing that could make it &s;ucce&s;sful, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> provincial troops cooperated with him &s;o cordially, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> there appeared &s;carcely any chance for its mi&s;carriage. Accordingly the French empire in North America be|came &s;ubject to Great Britain.</P>
